TRANSPARENCY MOMENT: One of my mottos  for 2023 is “Just Be.” As I stepped into 2023, I was intentional about not setting any “big” goal for the year. Instead, I’ve chosen to consciously embrace everything in front of me as is at this exact moment. Often times we find ourselves always chasing something…a new job, bigger clients, more campaigns, more money, a new this or that…it’s always something. And this year, that is changing for me. This is the very first year I’ve decided not to chase anything because I’ve been tremendously blessed with what’s in front of me thus far. My family, my faith, my health, my job, my business…everything I have and have done up to this point is ENOUGH and my goal for 2023 is to shift my mindset to understand that if I nothing “big” ever happens again in my life, I am still content. And that mindset shift is a complete game changer. 

So 2023 is all about basking in the blessings of today and remembering that everything I need is right in front of me❤️

This little girl can’t get enough of her mama 🥰 she wants to be attached to my hip at all times, but interestingly enough, her clinginess has shown me how great a gift our presence is to our little ones💕

Whether it’s standing between my legs while I’m washing the dishes. Or plopping on my lap every time I sit down. Or following me to the bathroom. Or asking for my hand so that she can walk me over to her toys to play with her every chance she gets.…I’m reminded everyday that our kids really want one thing, and that’s our presence. 

Olivia could care less about fancy toys, cute clothes, a nice house, how much money we make, or fancy vacations…all she wants is my time and presence and as a result, I’ve reprioritized my entire life to make sure I give her as much of that as possible.

What does that look like for me as a working mom? 

Shutting my computer at 5:15 sharp- I even have a hold on my work calendar that says “time with my daughter” so my team knows I’m completely unavailable 

Limiting work on the weekend- As a content creator, working on the weekend is unfortunately inevitable, but if I do work it’s no more than 2 hours 

At least 30 minutes of distraction-free playtime everyday- she lights UP when I get on the floor and play whatever it is she wants to play🥹

Intentional quality time- like walks through the neighborhood, dinner dates with just the two of us, trips to Target😂

Lots of cuddles, lots of kisses, and lotsssss of silly time- I’m talking singing made up songs, making silly faces, yelling at the top of our lungs…this is my favorite time with her because she really brings out the kid in me

Simply letting my 1 year old be a 1 year old- understanding there’s gonna be messes, spills, tantrums, screaming, ect and that’s okay. Kids will be kids.

Olivia has taught me to slow down, to not take life too seriously and most importantly, that time is a gift and I there’s no better way to spend it than to be fully present❤️ I used to think having a “clingy kid” was a negative thing but babyyyy…I pray Olivia always wants to be attached to my hip because it means I must be doing something right!

After I had my daughter, I felt so guilty for being a “bad friend” . My priorities had changed, my free time was limited, it took me days to reply to texts and calls, and some days I didn’t even have the energy to “check in” on them because I would be drowning myself.

But my friends never ONCE made me feel bad about any of that. They extended me the kind of grace I should’ve been showing myself because they knew my heart, and I am so grateful to them for that. 

Now that things are more consistent and we’ve gotten our new normal all figured out,  I made it one of my goals this year to make a conscious effort to not only do a better job at showing up for those who mean the world to me, but to also show them just how much they mean to me with even the simplest acts of kindness….like inviting them over for breakfast and mimosas.

Me and one of my best friends of almost 20 years (🤯) hadn’t been able to make our schedules work to get together the past few weeks, so I invited her and her mom (aka my second mom) over for breakfast and mimosas. Honestly, the breakfast was super simple, our house was a wreck and honestly I didn’t have much to give that day because Liv kept us up all night and was fussy ALL morning 🫠 but I did it…and it meant the world to me that they spent a few hours out of their day to just come over, catch up, laugh and love on each other like we always do. 

So here’s to more of making a conscious effort to show your people how much you love them. Doesn’t have to be some grand gesture…remember even the littlest things have the greatest impact ❤️

When I was pregnant, I knew the one thing I didn’t want to lose after having my baby was my love for traveling. Traveling is what fuels me, keeps me creative and quite frankly, it keeps me sane😂

If only you guys knew how many times I heard “enjoy it now because once the baby arrives you won’t be able to do that” or “get ready, having a baby will slow you down”🙃 while that might be the case for some, I’m living proof that that doesn’t have to be the case for all. 

In fact…me and @thedeonknox traveled more during our daughter’s first year than we’d ever traveled during any other year in the entire 13+ years we’ve been together 😳 that’s wild!

My trips during Olivia’s first year included girls trips, baecations, family trips and even a trip for work. I’m all about balance and I find that each of those types of trips are super important because they each feed my soul in a unique way.

I’m such a huge advocate for moms taking the time to do those special things that bought them joy before kids or even before marriage…because before we were wives or moms, we were *insert your name here*. 

So whether it’s traveling, weekly dance classes, regular happy hours with your girls, spa trips or even keeping your hair and nails did…remember to lean on your tribe and do what you gotta do to take care of YOU, mama❤️

One of the things I cherish most about my marriage is that @thedeonknox and I are true partners. He doesn’t let me carry the load alone and vice versa.

I’ll be the first to admit that it took us MONTHS after having Olivia to truly find our rhythm with this whole parenting thing. 

During those first few months taking care of Olivia came so naturally, but taking care of and supporting each other was suddenly foreign territory.

It wasn’t until we had a sincere heart to heart one night that we realized we’d been struggling because what “support” looked like to us pre-baby was COMPLETELY different post-baby.

We all know kids require A LOT, so after having Olivia, we realized that simply showing up for each other as we completed even the simplest tasks was all we really needed.

Our night routine is one of the areas we’ve really found our rhythm and demonstrate true partnership because we always tackle it together. Every single night. Neither of us does it alone and I love that. 

We do these tasks simultaneously…so for example m, while Deon is doing bathtime, I’m washing dishes or while I’m putting her down for bed, he’s tidying up. Not to mention it makes the night go so much faster and smoother so that we still have enough time for each after a Olivia is down😝

SOUND ON 🔊 It was on my heart this morning to share a few words of encouragement to all of the ladies out there who may work in a space where they feel like they don’t belong or worse, feel like they don’t deserve to be there. Sis, I’m here to remind you, that you DO.

As a black women in in a white male dominated industry, I’ll be the first to admit that showing fully as yourself isn’t always the easiest 🥴 

When I first entered the workforce in my early 20’s, I felt like I had to be a different version of myself to really thrive in my career. I would “act” how I thought I should act, speak how I thought I should speak, dress how I thought I should dress…and it sucked.

Not to mention a former white male supervisor called me aggressive during a performance review (🙄 this is a story for another day), further discouraging me from showing up as “Kyra”.

…But then I turned 30😂 and babyyyy when I turned 30 that was a wrap on that shelled version of myself. I decided then that I would show up fully, boldly and proudly in alllll areas of my life, including professional, and if others had an issue with all this black girl magic… that was on them.

So I encourage you today to show up fully, boldly, proudly and authentically you…why? Because you ARE enough.

Tell yourself “I belong here, I deserve to be here and I deserve all of the wins and successes that are coming my way.”

Your name is being mentioned in rooms your feet haven’t yet entered and your best is going to land you exactly where you need to be.

Sis, you got this❤️

TRANSPARENCY MOMENT: Marriages go through “seasons” and just like the weather, marital seasons change constantly and will even sneak up on you without you even knowing. Over the years, @thedeonknox and I have realized that it’s not just important to identify what season your marriage is currently in, but to also identify what that season looks like, what will change and what’s needed from the other to get through it.

Deon and I are currently in a “growing season”. We go through a growing season every few years so we know exactly what to expect by now, but it has not been easy. We’ve been sowing seeds behind the scenes on a project that will set the foundation for our family’s legacy and build true generational wealth, and as a result, we’ve been working a lot more, going out less on the weekends, getting less sleep, having fewer date nights, ect…and it’s been tough, especially since we have a toddler this time around.

But one thing about us, is we both understand the importance of making temporary sacrifices for a long term gain. It may not be “fun” or “pretty” right now, but we know this season won’t last long. Because we communicate openly and honestly, We’re always on the same page and have managed to keep our eyes on the vision we have for our family…while still showing up fully for our girls. 

We may be tired, but we know that we will one day be able to reap the rewards of the seeds were sowing now. Until then we’ll keep putting In the  work and showing up the best way we now how for ourselves and our family🤍

Despite Summer coming to an end, this Texas heat is still no joke 🥵 With daily temperatures still in the 90’s, it’s my job to keep my daughter cool and safe. A child’s body temperature rises three to five times faster than an adult’s does. They are more vulnerable to heatstroke and when left in cars by parents or caregivers, it can turn deadly….and I refuse to let that happen. #ad

I play my part by not only checking my back seat every single time before getting out of the car, but also by using my daughter’s favorite toy as a tool to never forget her in the back seat. Her doll is not just a toy but a lifesaving tool.

Heavy on the “not a nurturing bone in my body”😂 because whew, becoming an instant mom at 23 was…interesting, but we here! 🫶🏽 after I posted the now viral reel of me helping Brilynn get ready for her sweet 16, so many people asked me how we got that that point….How we built a close relationship. And the answer is simple…I intentionally built a relationship with her outside of my husband. 

Even when Deon and I were just dating, I would take Brilynn for ice cream, take her to the nail salon or even take her shopping….just us girls. And now almost 14 years later, we have the closest relationship that I’m so grateful for.

Brilynn calls me randomly during the week to catch me up on all the high school tea and will often ask for advice on boys and friends😂 She feels comfortable telling me things I never felt telling my parents growing up (sometimes a lil more than I need to know🙃😂) and will tell me how much she appreciates our talks. We joke all the time about being a millennial vs. gen z and she loves to make fun of how things were for me “back in my  day”😩 She’s even named me “mama bear” and you know what, I’m not mad at it😂 because that is the relationship I always wanted for us. 

Now it’s not always easy, especially when you have to be the bad guy, but I truly believe that building my own relationship with her over the years has allowed her to still respect me even when I’m correcting or disciplining her. And that’s honestly all my mama heart could ask for🤍

TRANSPARENCY MOMENT: My bonus daughter got the unhealed, inexperienced version of me and yet somehow all these years later we stand here, side by side, as ride or dies🤞🏾 I don’t play about this one here. As most of you know, I became an “instant mom” at 23 years old and I didn’t have a clue what I was doing. Deon and I got married fresh out of college and I found it challenging to be a mother figure while still figuring my ish out. We didn’t have much, were just starting our careers, practically living check to check and didn’t have money for a lot of luxuries. I occasionally find myself feeling guilty when I think about the fact her younger sister will have a slightly different childhood than her because we have “more” now than we did when she was Olivia’s age.… but that’s a story for another day. What’s important is that we’ve worked our butts off to give her the world now because it’s never too late.

Brilynn never lacked love from her dad or I, but I will admit the nurturing part did not come easy to me in the beginning. Brilynn showed me grace, even at such a young age, and I don’t think I could ever thank her enough for allowing me to grow into the bonus mom she deserved🫶🏽

Mamas it’s so easy to play “shoulda,  woulda, coulda” when we think about the past, but we have to remind ourselves that growth, experience and healing is essential for a reason. Just as she showed me grace, I have to show it to myself as well and remind myself our journey happened exactly as it should. Because if it didn’t, we wouldn’t be here today. Sharing inside jokes, calling me randomly during the week spilling all the high school tea and having heart to heart talks when she needs it most😂

This girl here is the reason I am the woman and mama I am today💕
